  "opinion": "As a 45-year-old electrician from Philadelphia, I see fake content on social media as a real problem, but I think we can handle it with common sense and community effort. I only spend about an hour a day online, mostly checking in with family and friends or sharing updates from my volunteer work, so I'm not drowning in information, but I still come across things that don't seem right. My approach is simple: I don't share anything unless I'm sure it's true, and I rely on trusted sources like my church or local news. For example, if I see a post about a safety issue in our neighborhood, I'll check with neighbors or the community center before passing it along. I believe in being kind and helpful, so if someone shares fake news, I might gently point them to a fact-checking site or share what I know from my own experience. As a married mom with one child, I'm especially careful about what I expose my family to online; we talk about not believing everything we see and sticking to reliable information. My hobbies like board games and volunteering teach me to work together and think things through, which helps in spotting fakes. Overall, I think managing fake content is about staying grounded, trusting your gut, and looking out for each other—just like we do in our real-life communities.",
